  "prompt": "Vasoconstriction index of clobetasone butyrate?",
  "response": "Clobetasone butyrate is a mid-potency topical corticosteroid used for its anti-inflammatory and vasoconstriction effects. The vasoconstriction index (VI) or blanching index is a measure used to compare the potency of topical corticosteroids based on their ability to cause vasoconstriction (blanching of the skin). \n\nThe vasoconstriction index for clobetasone butyrate, commonly found in formulations like Eumovate, typically falls within the mid-potency range. While exact indices or values can vary depending on the formulation and study, clobetasone butyrate is generally considered less potent than higher classified corticosteroids such as betamethasone or clobetasol, which have higher vasoconstriction indices.\n\nIf you need a precise vasoconstriction index value for clobetasone butyrate, it would be best to refer to specific scientific studies or pharmacological resources that detail comparative profiles of topical corticosteroids.",
